TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Theory of Subgroups in Work Teams
AU  - Carton, Andrew M.
AU  - Cummings, Jonathon N.
Y1  - 2012/07/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2009.0322
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2009.0322
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 441
EP  - 470
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Although subgroups are a widely studied component of work teams, much of the literature on subgroups has remained loosely connected and key questions remain unanswered. We integrate research on faultlines, diversity, and intergroup processes to develop a theory composed of a typology of subgroups and a depiction of the formation, processes, and outcomes associated with subgroups. The key insight from our theory is that subgroups are characterized by three underlying factors: identity, resources, and knowledge.
AB  - Although subgroups are a widely studied component of work teams, much of the literature on subgroups has remained loosely connected and key questions remain unanswered. We integrate research on faultlines, diversity, and intergroup processes to develop a theory composed of a typology of subgroups and a depiction of the formation, processes, and outcomes associated with subgroups. The key insight from our theory is that subgroups are characterized by three underlying factors: identity, resources, and knowledge.
