TY  - JOUR
T1  - Catching Falling Stars: A Human Resource Response to Social Capital's Detrimental Effect of Information Overload on Star Employees
AU  - Oldroyd, James B.
AU  - Morris, Shad S.
Y1  - 2012/07/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2010.0403
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2010.0403
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 396
EP  - 418
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Because star employees are more visible and productive, they are likely to be sought out by others and develop an information advantage through their abundant social capital. However, not all of the information effects of stardom are beneficial. We theorize that stars' robust social capital may produce an unintended side effect of information overload. We highlight the role of human resource management in minimizing the effects of information overload for stars, and we discuss avenues for future research.
AB  - Because star employees are more visible and productive, they are likely to be sought out by others and develop an information advantage through their abundant social capital. However, not all of the information effects of stardom are beneficial. We theorize that stars' robust social capital may produce an unintended side effect of information overload. We highlight the role of human resource management in minimizing the effects of information overload for stars, and we discuss avenues for future research.
