TY  - JOUR
T1  - Understanding Input Events: A Model of Employees' Responses to Requests for Their Input
AU  - Richardson, Hettie A.
AU  - Taylor, Shannon G.
Y1  - 2012/07/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2010.0327
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2010.0327
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 471
EP  - 491
VL  - 37
IS  - 3
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - To understand employees' responses to requests for their input, we describe cognitive and self-regulatory processes that make up ?input events.? Within the context of dynamic competing demands for employees' limited resources, we propose event-level features as determinants of the choices made on receiving an input request, illuminating whether and when employees provide input and how much thought goes into input formulation. We further consider the influence of individual characteristics on susceptibility to bias when making such choices.
AB  - To understand employees' responses to requests for their input, we describe cognitive and self-regulatory processes that make up ?input events.? Within the context of dynamic competing demands for employees' limited resources, we propose event-level features as determinants of the choices made on receiving an input request, illuminating whether and when employees provide input and how much thought goes into input formulation. We further consider the influence of individual characteristics on susceptibility to bias when making such choices.
